<raw><![CDATA[    Investing.com – U.S. stocks were down on Thursday as markets were swept with a fresh wave of fear over Greece's debt crisis, after data showed that the Aegean nation's budget deficit was wider than previously thought.During early U.S. trade, the Dow Jones Industrial Average was down 0.52%, the S&P 500 index shed 0.68% and the Nasdaq Composite index was down 0.66%.Earlier in the day, Eurostat, the EU statistics agency, revised up Greece's 2009 budget deficit to 13.6% of gross domestic product from 12.7%.The Greek/German 10-year government bond yield spread grew to 562 basis points in the wake of the data, to its widest in 12 years. Meanwhile, the cost of insuring Greek debt from default jumped to record highs.Wireless chipmaker Qualcomm was among the worst performers. The firm shed 6.17% after its third quarter forecast fell short of market expectations.Meanwhile, stock markets in Europe also slumped: France’s CAC 40 was down 1.2%; Germany's DAX dropped 0.99%; Britain's FTSE 100 was down 0.92%; and the EURO STOXX 50 slid 1.59%.The revelation about Greece's finances offset upbeat U.S. data on unemployment claims and existing home sales. Earlier Thursday, official reports showed that Sales of U.S. previously owned homes rose in March for the first time in four months and that the number of Americans filing claims for unemployment benefits fell last week.             ]]></raw>
